{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 To use this script, simply name your markers with an @ symbol at the start, followed by a number, then shift+alt+click on the ruler near a marker\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 For example, you can have markers named:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 @24 <- This would jump to track number 24 when you shift+alt+click on the ruler near that marker\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 @47 Impact <- This would jump to track number 47, ignoring the additional text after your marker number wildcard\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Alt on PC = Option on Mac\par}
}

